Yoga was never meant to be a finite practice, 
confined to a mat, 
to a studio,

to share that frequency, 
to experience that frequency
 of pure absolute consciousness, ease, space, bliss.
 
And to walk upon the Earth as an breathing, living expression of that.

Big 6 lymph activation & some energizing breathing

Let me know how it makes you feel
💜💜💜

I’d like to introduce you to this game changer! 

The big 6 lymphatic activation as taught to me by @stopchasingpain 

Save this post. Share it with your friends and family. Teach it to everyone.

Learn the order. The order is very important. Start under the left collarbone, then above…

Play around with pressure, technique, duration.
Have fun with that part.
The basic instruction is 10 “rubs” & 10 pats in each location.

Help unclog the major hubs of the lymphatic system and improve your body’s capacity to remove wastes and deliver nutrients. Plus, it can make you feel energized and refreshed 🥰

For an added bonus - spend more time with your abdomen.

Also, feel free to use a tool; a gua sha, a massage ball, pressure point stimulator, etc…

It doesn’t take long
Do it daily.
At least once

And let me know in the comments, how it made you feel.

It makes me feel energized and grateful for my body.

Thank you, Dr. Perry - I’ll see you soon 💪🏼🙌🏼

Our deep consciousness knows our own body on every level
and is continuously trying to communicate that inner knowing to us.
 
There are a few issues at play here that disrupt our ability to observe and receive that sacred information. 
 
One is, we have forgotten how to listen without fear and without agenda.
We also struggle with understanding the difference between caring for our bodies and caring for our desires.
The last is this sense of urgency, which is oddly coupled with a crippling attachment to perfection. 
 
We can apply the same remedy to all of these challenges. 
We must slow down and get quiet.
And we must return to the breath.
 
Slow down enough to notice the moment we judge and react.
Get quiet enough to hear what is beyond the active, surface-level thoughts & beyond our programming and conditioning.
Breathing and feeling, observing and responding.
 
Slow down enough to notice when we would rather manipulate the information & continue with a certain behavior.
Get quiet enough to breathe & feel and mourn the loss of a harmful activity or an old version of ourselves.
 
Slow down enough to recognize we are not designed to sustain this inhuman level of information sharing & output without pause.
Get quiet enough to become aware of the harmful conditioning of comparison and competition.

What we become aware of, we can choose to release. 
And through this release, we can return to collaboration, sharing, and abundance.
 
When we are not able to hear the messages of our deep consciousness, it is reminder to slow down, to get quiet, to return to the breath and begin again.

Regarding Bone Broth vs Stock. Bone broth is made with specific bones that include connective tissue which breaks down in the broth as collagen and amino acids. Stocks are made from stock bones that do not include connective tissue. Bone broth is cooked for around 48 hours while stock is only cooked for 1-6. The extra cooking time allows for the assimilation of nutrients into the broth.

Kale Broccoli Soup
Serves 6

Ingredients:
2 large bunches of broccoli cut into florets, stems peeled and cut into chunks
1 bunch of kale (any type) stemmed and chopped into small pieces (@3 cups)
1 cup yellow or white onion chopped
2 cloves of garlic minced
8 cups of chicken or vegetable broth. I prefer chicken bone broth here.
¼ teaspoon red pepper flakes
¼ cup fresh lemon juice
¼ teaspoon maple syrup
¾ teaspoon himalaya or sea salt
2 tablespoons avocado oil 

Instructions:
1.	In a large pot bring 6 quarts of water to boil with 1⁄2 teaspoon of salt. Place the broccoli in a metal colander and plunge into the boiling water. Cook just until tender but firm and bright green. About 1 minute. 
2.	Remove broccoli from the boiling water and immediately immerse the broccoli in ice water to retain the bright color
3.	Heat the oil in a medium sauté pan over medium heat. Add the onions and a pinch of salt and sauté the onions until golden about 10 minutes. 
4.	Add the garlic and the red pepper flakes. Continue to sauté for another minute until aromatic. 
5.	Add the kale and a pinch of salt. Cook for one minute until the kale turns bright green. Immediately remove the pan from the heat.
6.	 In a blender add one-third of the broth, one-third broccoli and the kale mixture. Blend until smooth. When the color changes from pale green to vivid emerald green that’s your cue to turn off the blender.
7.	Pour into a clean pot and repeat until everything has been blended.
8.	Add the lemon juice and remaining salt and the maple syrup int the last blender batch.
9.	Stir and reheat the soup over a low heat.

Optional- garnish with cashew or coconut cream

⭐️NEW EPISODE ⭐️ BIRTH STORY 
Erika @erikahalweil gave birth to her first child in the hospital and was labeled a “weirdo”  and stamped as “difficult” for her birth plan intentions.  When the hospital staff tried to take her baby away in order to administer the Vitamin K shot and Erythromycin eye ointment, she refused, holding her baby close as the staff tried to pull the baby from Erika’s arms. Next came the call to CPS (Child Protective Services), putting Erika on a government watch list as a threat to her child’s well-being. As a long-time yoga practitioner and deep spiritualist, Erika shares her perspective on birth as a one-of-a-kind opportunity to embrace discomfort and release the notion of separation from oneness.

Hear everyone. Listen to yourself @downtobirthshow

This is about recognizing the intense chemicals, and debilitating toxins, that have invaded our seen and unseen landscape. 
 
We can see the harmful effect of toxic greed which has spread through all things, including agriculture. 
Big business farming has separated us from the knowledge, the ancient, harmonious wisdom, of the land - the same way organized religion has separated us from our innate spirituality. 
 
So again, I encourage you to be careful, to be mindful, to be aware of, what you are putting in your body in the form of food, liquid, thought, idea, company, daily structure.
 
Be vigilant, but not restrictive. 
Be aware, but not judgmental. 
Be an active participant, but remain receptive. 
Release the need for certainty, but consciously cultivate discernment.

Whatever we cultivate in times of ease, we gather as strength for the times of change.
- Jack Kornfield
 
Build your physical, emotional, mental, energetic,
 and spiritual foundation during the good times, during the sunny days, during any perceived peaceful moment. 
As if you were consciously stocking up, accumulating, tools and practices, and becoming familiar with them. 
So that you have this stockpile.
So that you have this awareness.
So that you have this familiarity.
So that you have this faith and trust.
 
We need to stop planning during the storm. 
We need to stop trying to organize, and to acquire, and to learn during the most challenging times.
From within a state of overwhelm and exhaustion.
Become aware of your habit and tendency to distract yourself during the best of times. 
What are you distracting yourself from?
Is it the fear of the good times fading away and the bad times returning? 
Instead of distracting yourself, instead of escaping, 
try activating, 
try committing,
try directing,
try appreciating,
and through that appreciation…
try acquiring strength, comfort, safety, wisdom.
 
What does it feel like to recognize your body as your temple?
What shifts when your recognize your body and mind as sacred?
Where does your focus go?
What becomes your highest priority?
Can you recognize the foundation for all of this is pure love…for self and other?

Yoga practice is so unique because it allows you to travel inside your body, 
through sensation, 
through breath, 
through awareness. 
 
You get to discover, and uncover, everything that exists within you. 
If you believe, or at least agree with, the famous saying 
“be the change, you wish to see in the world” - 
then, you need to remain curious, you need to be courageously honest, you need to know, what is inside your being. 

Is there physical density? Is there uneasiness? 
Is there fear? Is there doubt?
Is there frustration? Is there blame? 
Is there anger? Is there pain? 
Is there longing? Is there striving? 
Is there disconnect?

How will you ever know, if you avoid?
 
If you avoid through shallow breathing…if you avoid through resting on the outside of a situation, by holding yourself at arms length, by clinging to a certainty that limits your worldview and lived experience, by choosing to allow only a small percentage of what is, to penetrate?
 
Let this practice be the ceremony guiding you back, 
through the disconnect, 
to the Self Love & acceptance
that is essential to healing; 
that is essential to happiness; 
that is essential to health; 
that is all that truly exists
in this moment.

How you nourish yourself is how you choose to give love to yourself and to your body. 
We can nourish with food and the cells perceive this food has love. 
We can nourish with connection, with breath, with movement, with touch, with safe spaces with others. 
We can nourish with the sun, with fresh air, 
with clean water. 
We can nourish with uplifting information in the form of beauty, art, poetry, high-level math, science, philosophy, mythology, music, heartfelt tradition.
We can nourish with space and silence. 
We can also nourish with darkness and rest.

How do you choose to nourish yourself? 
What kind of self are you creating? 
What kind of release are you encouraging, are you inviting, to allow for the opening, for the rebirth, for the new embodiment?

The simpler the concept, 
the more challenging the execution.
 
Every experience is here for our greatest good. 
Everything is an opportunity to bring us closer to a clear understanding of truth.
Everything is here to allow us a chance to observe when we are living in alignment with our highest priority or when we get derailed.
 
Getting derailed is a chance to see, to feel, to experience, how we can mistakenly chose to reject our purpose, our integrity, our intention.
Even with the most clear intention and objective, 
it is so easy to get distracted, 
it is so easy to be deceived by the lower self’s need for the familiar, for the fleeting, short term ease.
 
Knowing this, we can welcome every experience 
- without judgment, without taking it personally, without justification - 
we can open up to truly see what we’ve chosen, and how it feels; 
to recognize how we may allow ourselves to be guided away from our intention, our direction, our highest aspiration. 
And then, to recognize how we have the same opportunity, the same ability, the same choice, to guide ourselves back.
 
Understanding this, we must be very clear about discarding, and releasing, perfectionism in all of its forms. 

Perfectionism cannot exist in this moment. 

In this moment, there is only breath and feeling and the infinite capacity to choose.
 
This human experience is a process and it is all welcome.

Get back to Nature & 
let all of the unnecessary things drop away - 
all the clutter, all the excess, all the yearning and striving, 
the feelings of insufficiency, the isolation, the self-judgment. 
Let go of what’s familiar, of what’s convenient, of what limits you. 
Let go and rediscover.
 
Get back to Nature by revealing yourself to Nature - 
to the sun, to the wind, to the stars, to the trees, to the wild grasses, the flowers and fruits, the seeds and the fires and floods of new beginning.

Only the untainted eye of Nature can see into our beings. Can see the untapped power and resources that will usher us into the next moment with vitality and possibility. 
Let there be communication between our bodies and all the bodies - earthly and celestial.
 
Nature gets more intelligent with time, it learns and adapts and evolves. If we are Nature, we have that same capacity, to learn and adapt and evolve through every exposure, every experience. 

Do not fear. 
Welcome everything, 
with faith and grounding and the breath moving through you.
 
We are here to learn
We are here to experience
We are here to feel
To love
To let go
To begin again
To rise from the ashes
To lay down roots
To sprout wings
 
This is the lifetime where we release fear
Where we release our armor
Where we release our judgment
Where we choose to step back into harmony with Nature
And become boundless once more
 
Free and creative and expansive and filled with light

to a welcoming self-love, 
to a perpetual release of judgment, assumptions, blame, agendas, timelines, score cards, comparisons of any kind
 
it is an excavation of fear
 
it is a platform, an opportunity, an experiment in exposing yourself completely for the purpose of revealing what is not in alignment, what can be cast off, processed, released, transmuted for the evolution of 
your Soul’s journey - 
which is your most blessed, and sacred, work in this lifetime
 
it is truly a gift to be alive
to be right in the thick of it
where everything is felt
where everything is observed & received & experienced
 
let go of every fear
every single one
 
and if you hear its murmurings, allow yourself to sense it, to meet it, to get to know it, to learn from it
and then
to bless it
and to release it
 
so that you may see the boundless beauty in all things
in all aspects of yourself
in every moment
